                ['In SOLID principles, the "O" stands for Open/Closed Principle. What does this mean in practice?', ['Classes should be open for extension but closed for modification — use inheritance/composition instead of changing existing code', 'Only open-source software should be used', 'Methods should be open to multiple parameter types', 'Classes should always be open for any modifications'], 0],
                ['A team refactors a monolithic application into microservices. Which challenge is MOST likely to emerge?', ['Distributed system complexity — network latency, data consistency, service discovery, and debugging across services', 'Reduced code reuse across services', 'Inability to deploy services independently', 'Higher memory usage per service'], 0],
                ['A code review reveals the following: a class has methods for user authentication, email sending, PDF generation, and database queries. Which SOLID principle is being violated?', ['Single Responsibility Principle — the class has too many unrelated responsibilities', 'Liskov Substitution Principle', 'Interface Segregation Principle', 'Dependency Inversion Principle'], 0],
                ['A development team implements the Repository Pattern. What is the PRIMARY benefit?', ['Abstracts data access logic, making it easier to switch storage backends or test with mock data', 'Increases database query performance', 'Eliminates the need for an ORM', 'Ensures data is always cached in memory'], 0],
